statement.p:
Suppose that the following information is known about the functions f,
g, x^2, and x^3:






      \displaystyle \int_0^2 f(x) \, dx = -3;
      \displaystyle \int_2^5 f(x) \, dx = 2







      \displaystyle \int_0^2 g(x) \, dx = 4;
      \displaystyle \int_2^5 g(x) \, dx = -1







      \displaystyle \int_0^2 x^2 \, dx = \frac{8}{3};
      \displaystyle \int_2^5 x^2 \, dx = \frac{117}{3}







      \displaystyle \int_0^2 x^3 \, dx = 4;
      \displaystyle \int_2^5 x^3 \, dx = \frac{609}{4}

subsection.p:
Since \Delta x = \frac{b-a}{n}, we can thus write

  R_n =\mathstrut \amp (f(x_1) + f(x_2) + \cdots + f(x_n))\cdot \frac{b-a}{n}
  =\mathstrut \amp (b-a) \frac{f(x_1) + f(x_2) + \cdots + f(x_n)}{n}
.

solution.p:
Therefore, the area between the curves y=x^2+1 and y=x+3 is given by the following quantity:
\int_{-1}^{2}(x+3)dx-\int_{-1}^{2}(x^2+1)dx=\int_{-1}^{2}\left((x+3)-(x^2+1)\right)dx
\mathstrut \amp=\int_{-1}^{2}(-x^2+x+2)dx \mathstrut \amp= -\frac{1}{3}x^3+\frac{1}{2}x^2+2x \right|_{-1}^{2} \mathstrut \amp= -\frac{1}{3}(2)^3+\frac{1}{2}(2)^2+2(2)-\left(-\frac{1}{3}(-1)^3+\frac{1}{2}(-1)^2+2(-1)\right) \mathstrut \amp =-\frac{8}{3}+2+4-\left(\frac{1}{3}+\frac{1}{2}-2\right) \mathstrut \amp= \frac{9}{2}
